# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aberdeen
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] In 1964, there was an outbreak of typhoid in the city of Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] The first two cases were identified on 20 May 1964; eventually over 400 cases were diagnosed and the patients were quarantined at the City Hospital in Urquhart Road, Woodend Hospital in Eday Road, and Tor-na-Dee Hospital in Milltimber which was used as an overflow hospital for typhoid cases.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] There were three deaths connected with the outbreak.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] Dr Ian MacQueen, the Medical Officer of Health for Aberdeen, became well known in the media for his twice-daily briefings.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] The outbreak was eventually traced to contaminated tinned corned beef from Rosario, Argentina and sold in the city's branch of the Scottish grocery chain William Low.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] Pollution from the waters of the Uruguay River (which flows into the Río de la Plata) appeared to be the source of the contamination, probably through water entering a defective tin through a small puncture.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] The infected meat then contaminated a meat slicing machine within the William Low shop, leading to the spread of the disease.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] The bacteria multiplied further in the meats as they were placed near a window and exposed to sunlight.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] The reputation of Aberdeen as a safe city to visit, live and work in was briefly harmed by the media coverage of the outbreak.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] In July 1964, following the end of the outbreak, Queen Elizabeth II made a high-profile visit to boost morale and to help rehabilitate the city's reputation.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] An official enquiry and report into the outbreak was commissioned by the Secretary of State for Scotland.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] The enquiry was headed by Sir David Milne and his published findings became known as the Milne Report.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] The reputation of William Low was irrevocably damaged within Aberdeen and the city's store, the source of the outbreak, closed for good three years later.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] Dundee-based company William Low subsequently opened many other stores around Scotland, but remained absent from Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] William Low was eventually taken over by Tesco in 1994.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] Public perceptions of the safety of Fray Bentos tinned meats also contributed to significantly diminished income.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] The outbreak was successfully handled, although there were three fatalities confirmed.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] The outbreak drew attention to the need for better standards of hygiene, notably in the cleaning of food processing machinery.
[src:aberdeen/1964-aberdeen-typhoid-outbreak] The University of Aberdeen went on to develop an international reputation in the field of disease control, notably in the appointment of Professor Hugh Pennington to the post of Professor of Bacteriology from 1979 until his retirement in 2003.
[src:aberdeen/1983-european-super-cup] The **1983 UEFA Super Cup** was a two-legged match contested between the 1982–83 European Cup winners Hamburger SV, and the 1982–83 European Cup Winners' Cup winners Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen/1983-european-super-cup] The first leg at the Volksparkstadion in Hamburg finished 0–0.
[src:aberdeen/1983-european-super-cup] In the second leg at Pittodrie Stadium, Aberdeen added their second European trophy with a 2–0 victory over the West Germans with goals coming from Mark McGhee and Neil Simpson.
[src:aberdeen/1983-european-super-cup] Aberdeen became the first Scottish team to win the UEFA Super Cup.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] The **1999 Open Championship** was a men's major golf championship and the 128th Open Championship, held from 15 to 18 July at the Carnoustie Golf Links in Angus, Scotland.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Paul Lawrie won his only major championship in a playoff over Jean van de Velde and Justin Leonard.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Lawrie, down by ten strokes at the start of the fourth round, completed the biggest final round comeback in major championship history, headlined by van de Velde's triple-bogey at the last hole.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Paul Lawrie completed the biggest final round comeback in major championship and PGA Tour history by coming back from 10 strokes behind in the final round, and winning the subsequent three-man playoff.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Jean van de Velde started the day with a five-stroke lead over Craig Parry and Justin Leonard, but trailed Parry by a stroke at the 12th hole, as Parry was −3 for the day through 11, while Van de Velde was +3.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] However, Parry could not escape the thick rough on the 12th hole on his way to a triple bogey while Van de Velde regained sole possession of the lead with a bogey.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Parry then bogeyed 13, drove into the fairway bunker at 14 to deny himself a birdie chance, and missed a two-foot (0.6 m) putt on 17 en route to a double bogey.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] He holed a bunker shot on 18 to finish one stroke out of the playoff.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] After the birdie on 14, Van de Velde missed the next three greens but got up-and-down each time to give himself a three stroke lead going into 18.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Van de Velde, who was in control through the latter half of the championship, held a seemingly insurmountable three-stroke lead going into the 72nd hole.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Despite the three-stroke lead van de Velde had going into the final hole, his name had not already been engraved into the Claret Jug, according to engraver Alex Harvey: "No, I didn't start engraving the Jug with his name.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Van de Velde teed off with a driver, which was heavily criticised by the ABC broadcast team, and pushed his shot far to the right, over the water bordering the right side of the 18th fairway, and onto the 17th hole.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] He later claimed that he thought the lead was only two strokes, which is why he chose not to go with a safe club, such as an iron.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Choosing not to simply lay up with a wedge, van de Velde went for the green on his second shot with a two iron.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] His second shot came to rest in an area of knee-deep rough after his ball bounced backward 50 yards off the grandstand next to the 18th green and off a rock in the Barry Burn.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Had the ball stayed in the grandstand he would have been able to drop without penalty.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Then the thick Carnoustie grass stifled him again, as his third shot went into the burn in front of the green.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Van de Velde took his shoes and socks off and entered the burn, considering an attempt to play the ball from the water.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] He decided against it and instead took a drop (fourth stroke), at which point he hit his fifth shot into one of the deep greenside bunkers.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] He pitched out safely and holed the six-foot putt on his seventh shot for a triple-bogey, which would trigger a three-man playoff between van de Velde, Lawrie, and Leonard.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Van de Velde's play on this hole is still widely considered to be the worst "choke" in golfing history, and some have even used the term "pulling a van de Velde" to describe similar events.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] The four-hole aggregate playoff was played on the final four holes (#15-18), three par fours and one par three (#16).
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] All three players hit poor drives on the first playoff hole.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] Van de Velde was forced to take an unplayable and took double bogey to fall one stroke behind Lawrie and Leonard who both had bogeys.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] All three players missed the green on the second playoff hole and took bogeys.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] On the third playoff hole, Van de Velde made birdie to briefly create a three-way tie, but Lawrie followed with a birdie of his own to take a one-stroke lead into the final playoff hole.
[src:aberdeen/1999-open-championship] On the final playoff hole, Van de Velde found the rough and Leonard found the water en route to bogeys while Lawrie hit a 4-iron to four feet for a clinching birdie and the championship.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The **2006 Commonwealth Games**, officially the **XVIII Commonwealth Games** and commonly known as **Melbourne 2006**, were an international multi-sport event for members of the Commonwealth held in Melbourne, Australia between 15 and 26 March 2006.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] It was the fourth time Australia had hosted the Commonwealth Games.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] It was also the largest sporting event to be staged in Melbourne, eclipsing the 1956 Summer Olympics in terms of the number of teams and athletes competing, and events being held.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] More than 4,000 athletes from 71 Commonwealth Games Associations took part in the event.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] Zimbabwe withdrew its membership from the Commonwealth of Nations and Commonwealth Games Federation on 8 December 2003 and so did not participate in the event.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] With 245 sets of medals, the Games featured 17 Commonwealth sports.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] These sporting events took place at 13 venues in the host city, two venues in Bendigo and one venue each in Ballarat, Geelong, Lysterfield Park and Traralgon.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The site for the opening and closing ceremonies was the Melbourne Cricket Ground, which was also used during the 1956 Olympics.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The mascot for the games was Karak, a red-tailed black cockatoo (a threatened species).
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The official song of the Games, "Together We Are One", was composed by the ARIA awardee Australian recording artist Delta Goodrem.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] During the closing ceremony of the games, President of the Commonwealth Games Federation Mike Fennell declared to the crowd "Melbourne, you are simply the best".
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] For the first time in the history of the Commonwealth Games, the Queen's Baton visited every single Commonwealth nation and territory taking part in the Games, a journey of 180,000 kilometres (110,000 miles).
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The relay ended when the Governor of Victoria, and former Commonwealth Games medallist, John Landy delivered the baton to Her Majesty the Queen at the Melbourne Cricket Ground during the opening ceremony.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The host nation Australia topped the medal table for the fifth time in the past five Commonwealth Games, winning the most golds (84) and most medals overall (221).
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] England and Canada finished second and third respectively.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The 2006 Commonwealth Games have been lauded as "best Commonwealth Games ever".
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] A KPMG analysis of 2006 Commonwealth Games found the event prompted an increase in gross state product of about A$1.6 billion over a 20-year period and employment of about 13,600 jobs.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] Having previously hosted the 1956 Olympics, Melbourne has hosted world sporting events such as the 1979 World Fencing Championships.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The city made a bid to host the 1996 Summer Olympics, but was unsuccessful in its bid to Atlanta.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] Following the failure of the Olympic bid, the city would later make plans to host the Commonwealth Games.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] During the 1998 Commonwealth Games in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, two cities initially expressed interest in hosting the event; Melbourne, Australia and Wellington, New Zealand.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] Wellington withdrew its bid, citing the costs involved with matching the bid plan presented by Melbourne, which became the default host without members of the Federation going to vote.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The following venues were used at the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The sport(s) that were played at that venue are listed after it.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] Early concerns arose about the large cost of staging the event, with projected costs likely to be over AU$1 billion and a high likelihood the Victorian taxpayer would have to cover the expense.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The cost was described in some local media as excessive.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] National Party leader Peter Ryan said that the Labor government should win "gold (medal) for burning money".
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] However, not all of this money was wasted.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The final costs for hosting the Games was AU$1.144 billion, and prior to the Games, accountants at KPMG were estimating that the gross income generated by this event could be as high as AU$1.5 billion.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] An athlete's village in the inner suburb of Parkville housed approximately 7,000 athletes and support staff during the Games, and has been transformed into commercial housing with a distinctly eco-friendly image.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The creation of this village attracted controversy, with critics claiming it was created by alienating public parkland, while proponents maintained that it represented the renewal of an otherwise derelict inner-city area.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The change from Daylight Saving Time to Standard Time in Australian states that follow it was delayed from 26 March to 2 April in 2006 to avoid affecting the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] In addition, state and private schools amended their usual term times to allow the first term holidays to coincide with the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] Melbourne's public transport system – train, tram and bus – ran to altered timetables with some amended or substituted services for the duration of the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] For the most part, timetabled services were unchanged but suffered due to higher loads.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] For the first time ever, the Melbourne 2006 Commonwealth Games appointed a Goodwill Partner, Plan International Australia.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] Both the Melbourne Cricket Ground and the Yarra River were centrepieces for the ceremony, which included many fireworks, and other spectacle.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The Games were opened by Elizabeth II, in her capacity as Head of the Commonwealth.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The Queen is also Head of State of a number of Commonwealth countries.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] Both the Melbourne Cricket Ground and the Yarra River were again centrepieces for the ceremony.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] Samresh Jung of India was given the David Dixon Award at the closing ceremony.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] He was the "Best Athlete of the 18th Commonwealth Games".
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The games were closed by The Earl of Wessex, Prince Edward.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] There were 71 countries, territories and bodies competing at the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The only difference is the roster between the 2006 Games and the 2002 Games was the absence of Zimbabwe, which had withdrawn from the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The 2006 Commonwealth Games included 17 sports, with 12 individual sports and 4 team sports.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] In total there are 245 events at the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The athletics, swimming, table tennis and weightlifting sports included fully integrated events for elite athletes with a disability (EAD).
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] These events were included in the official medal tally.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The logo of the 2006 Commonwealth Games is an image of 2 figures, which represents sport and culture, achievement and excellence, while the colours green, yellow, and red represents celebratory, fresh and youthfully optimistic character of Melbourne city.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The two figures in the logo joined to form a letter M, which is the initial letter of Melbourne, the games host city.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] On 20 March 2006, it was reported that two athletes had gone missing from the Commonwealth Games village: Tanzanian boxer Omari Idd Kimweri and Bangladeshi runner Mohammad Tawhidul Islam.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] On 22 March, it was reported that seven athletes from Sierra Leone (three women and four men) had also disappeared.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] A further seven Sierra Leonean athletes also went missing during the course of the Games, bringing the total runaway count to fourteen (two-thirds of the team).
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] Victoria Police believed that they had fled to Sydney where the Sierra Leonean community is much larger than Melbourne's.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] Two hours before the closing ceremony on 26 March, officials from the Cameroon team reported to police that nine of their members had also vanished.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] These incidents were not without precedent: 27 athletes similarly disappeared from the 2002 Commonwealth Games in Manchester, England (21 from Sierra Leone, 5 from Bangladesh and one from Pakistan), and over 80 athletes and officials overstayed their visas after the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] On request of Sierra Leone officials, the Commonwealth Games Federation cancelled those athletes' Games accreditation, allowing the Australian Department of Immigration and Multicultural Affairs (DIMA) to cancel their visas at midnight on 27 March, and begin investigating their disappearance.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] At 7.20 am on that day, New South Wales Police located six of the Sierra Leonean athletes in a house at Freshwater, near Manly Beach in Sydney.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] All six indicated they wished to seek political asylum in Australia, and were granted bridging visas by DIMA while their refugee applications were arranged.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The athletes claimed to have been subjected to violence and torture in their home country; seventeen-year-old Isha Conteh stated she could be forced into female genital cutting if she returned.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] On Tuesday 28 March, six further Sierra Leoneans turned themselves in to immigration authorities in Sydney and were also granted bridging visas.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] Two of the missing Cameroonian athletes were later found in Perth, Western Australia.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] The Stolenwealth Games were protests at the 1982 and 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] People were protesting because they believed that the Commonwealth Games led to the erasure of indigenous people.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] There were also problems with land rights.
[src:aberdeen/2006-commonwealth-games] These protests led to the creation of the Global Indigenous Games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The **2010 Commonwealth Games**, officially known as the **XIX Commonwealth Games** and commonly known as **Delhi 2010**, were an international multi-sport event for the members of the Commonwealth that was held in Delhi, India, from 3 to 14 October 2010.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] A total of 4352 athletes from 71 Commonwealth nations and dependencies competed in 21 sports and 272 events, making it the largest Commonwealth Games to date.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] It was also the largest international multi-sport event to be staged in Delhi and India, eclipsing the Asian Games in 1951 and 1982.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The opening and closing ceremonies were held at the Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, the main stadium of the event.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] It was the first time that the Commonwealth Games were held in India and the second time they were held in Asia after Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia in 1998.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The official mascot of the Games was Shera and the official song of the Games, "Jiyo Utho Badho Jeeto", was composed by Academy and Grammy awardee Indian recording artist A.R.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Preparation for the Games received widespread international media attention, with criticism being levelled against the organisers for the slow pace of work, as well as issues related to security and hygiene.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] In spite of threats of boycotts and athlete withdrawals however, all member nations of the Commonwealth of Nations participated in the event, with the exceptions of Fiji, which is suspended from the Commonwealth, and Tokelau, which didn't send a team.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The internationally acclaimed opening ceremony improved the image of the Games, and dispelled negative notions surrounding them, with many observers remarking that they began on an apprehensive note, but were an exceptional experience with a largely positive ending.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The President of the International Olympic Committee, Jacques Rogge, said that India had made a good foundation for a future Olympics bid, which was reiterated by the Australian Minister of Sports.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Commonwealth games Federation chief Mike Fennell stated that "Delhi delivered a fantastic Games".
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Some observers accused sections of the media of bias, unfair expectations, and negative reporting.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The final medal tally was led by Australia with 74 golds and 177 most medals overall.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The host nation India achieved its best performance ever at the Commonwealth Games, finishing second overall by winning 38 golds and 101 total medals.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Delhi was selected as the host city of the 2010 Commonwealth Games on 14 November 2003 during the CGF General Assembly in Montego Bay, Jamaica, defeating bid from Hamilton, Ontario, Canada.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] India's bid motto was *New Frontiers and Friendships*.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] India shifted the balance in its favour in the second round of voting with a promise that it would provide US$100,000 to each participating country, along with air tickets, boarding, lodging and transport.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The successful 2003 Afro-Asian Games held in Hyderabad was also seen as having shown that India has the resources, infrastructure and technical know-how to stage a big sporting event.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Meanwhile, Hamilton struggled with the notion a country would not be awarded two major multi-sport events in the same year, after Vancouver was awarded the 2010 Winter Olympics earlier in the year.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Delhi bid for the 1990 and 1994 Commonwealth Games but lost to Auckland and Victoria respectively.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The Hamilton bid was Canada's attempt to hold the games for the fifth time.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Singh also called for a revamp of the games' organising committees: Jarnail Singh, a former Secretary of the Government of India, was appointed as the chief executive officer and Indian Olympic Association president Suresh Kalmadi was appointed as head of the committee.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] In spite of delays and the corruption cases levied on the organisers, commentators stated that they were confident that India will successfully host the games and do so on time.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] At the launch of the Queen's Baton Relay in October 2009, the Business Club of India (BCI) was formed through the partnership of the organising committee, the Confederation of Indian Industry and the Federation of Indian Chambers of Commerce and Industry.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The BCI was formed to both market the Games and promote Indian business interests internationally.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Events took place at 12 competition venues.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] A total of 20 training venues were used in the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Of these 20, one was used for archery; three for aquatics; two for lawn bowls; two for netball; eight for rugby sevens, including seven venues within Delhi University; two for shooting; one for squash; two for table tennis; one for weightlifting, three for wrestling and two for tennis.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] A total of five venues were newly constructed for the event; the Dr.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Karni Singh Shooting Range, the Siri Fort Sports Complex, the Thyagaraj Sports Complex, the Yamuna Sports Complex as well as a rugby sevens facility in Delhi University Stadium.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] This does not include the two venues—the Indira Gandhi Sports Complex and Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium—that received major renovations or an uplift.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] All other venues had existed prior to the event.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The largest venue was the Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, with a capacity of 60,000, was the main venue of the event, hosting both the opening and the closing ceremonies.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] On the other hand, the Central Reserve Police Force (CRPF) Shooting Range located in Kadarpur had the smallest seating capacity, at 345.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] There were three main non-competition venues in the event, besides the Commonwealth Games Village; namely the Delhi 2010 Commonwealth Games Organising Committee Headquarters, the Main Media Centre, and the Games Family Hotel, Hotel Ashok.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The Commonwealth Games Village provided accommodation and training for athletes of the Games, and was opened from 23 September to 18 October 2010.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] It is located along the east bank of the River Yamuna, in proximity to competition and training venues as well as city landmarks, and is spread over an area of 63.5 hectares (157 acres).
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Comprising five main zones—the Residential Zone, the International Zone, the Training Area, the Main Dining and the Operational Zone—the Games Village, which was a non-smoking zone, was universally accessible particularly to accommodate para-sport athletes.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Free accommodation for all athletes at the Games Village, as well as free transport and other benefits, such as a free trip to the famed Taj Mahal and a reserved lane for participants on selected highways were provided.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The Games Village accommodated over 8,000 athletes and officials for the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The initial total budget estimated by the Indian Olympic Association in 2003 for hosting the Games was ₹16.2 billion (US$170 million).
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] In 2010, however, the official total budget soon escalated to an estimated ₹115 billion (US$1.2 billion), a figure which excluded non-sports-related infrastructure development.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Business Today magazine estimated that the Games cost ₹700 billion (US$7.3 billion).
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The 2010 Commonwealth Games was reportedly the most expensive Commonwealth Games ever.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] A four-lane flyway, 2.2 km (1.4 mi) stretch from Lodi Road to trans-Yamuna, linking the Games Village to the Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium was constructed which reduced the travelling time between the village and the Stadium to six minutes.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] In response to concerns over the large number of trains that pass by the Delhi metropolitan region daily, construction of road under-bridges and over-bridges along railway lines have been completed.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] To expand road infrastructure, flyovers, cloverleaf flyovers, and bridges were built to improve links for the Games and city in general.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Road-widening projects were finished with an emphasis being placed on expanding national highways.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] To improve traffic flow on existing roads, plans were made to make both the inner and outer Ring roads signal free.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] To support its commitment to mass transport, nine corridors have been identified and were constructed as High Capacity Bus Systems (for example, one from Ambedkar Nagar to Red Fort).
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Six of these corridors were expected to be operational in 2010.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Additionally, The Delhi Metro was expanded to accommodate more people and boost the use of public transport during the event.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The metro has extended to Gurgaon and the Noida area.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] For this large increase in the size of the network, Delhi Metro had deployed 14 tunnel boring machines.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Radio Frequency Identification (RFID) was used to tag vehicles in venue parking lots to help organise mass parking and increase security.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Indira Gandhi International Airport was modernised, expanded, and upgraded.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Costing nearly $1.95 billion, Terminal 3 has increased airport passenger capacity to more than 37 million passengers a year by 2010.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] A new runway has been constructed, allowing for more than 75 flights an hour.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] At more than 4400 metres long, it is one of Asia's longest.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The airport has been connected to the city via a six-lane expressway (Delhi–Gurgaon Expressway) and the $580 million Delhi Airport Metro Express line.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The organisers signed a Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) with the United Nations Environment Programme to show the intention to host a "sustainable games" and to take the environment into consideration when constructing and renovating venues.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Thyagaraj Stadium is intended to be a key example of environmentally considered construction.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] In opposition to this intention, a number of environmental controversies arose and the adverse ecological impact of various aspects of the games have been protested by city residents.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] City residents filed a public interest petition to the Supreme Court of India against the felling of 'heritage' trees in the Siri Fort area to make way for Games facilities.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The court appointed architect Charles Correa to assess the impact and he severely criticised the designs on ecological grounds.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] In spite of this, in April 2009 the Supreme Court allowed the construction on the grounds that "much time had been lost" and "the damage already caused to the environment could not be undone".
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The Commonwealth Games village, located on the flood plains of the Yamuna, has also been the subject of controversies about the flouting of ecological norms.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The Queen's Baton Relay began when the baton, which contains Elizabeth II's message to the athletes, left Buckingham Palace on 29 October 2009.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The baton arrived at the 2010 Games opening ceremony on 3 October 2010, after visiting the other 54 nations of the Commonwealth and travelling throughout India, reaching millions of people to join in the celebrations for the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The baton arrived in India on 25 June 2010 through the Wagah Border crossing from Pakistan.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The baton was designed by Michael Foley of Foley Designs and a graduate of the National Institute of Design.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] It is a triangular section of aluminium twisted into a helix shape and then coated with coloured soils collected from all the regions of India.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The coloured soils are a first for the styling of a Queen's Baton.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] A jewel-encrusted box was used to house the Queen's message, which was laser-engraved onto a miniature 18 carat gold leaf—representative of the ancient Indian 'patras.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The Queen's baton is ergonomically contoured for ease of use.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] It is 664 millimetres (26.1 in) high, 34 millimetres (1.3 in) wide at the base, and 86 millimetres (3.4 in) wide at the top and weighs 1,900 grams (67 oz).
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] In preparation for an influx of English-speaking tourists for the Games, the Delhi government implemented a program to teach English, and the necessary skills for serving tourists, to key workers—such as cab drivers, security workers, waiters, porters, and service staff.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] In the two years prior to the Games 2000 drivers were taught English.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] In addition to Delhi, the Indian Government plans to expand the program to teach people in local tourist destinations in other parts of India.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] To facilitate hassle-free sightseeing in Delhi, Delhi Tourism undertook the launch of India's very first Hop on Hop Off bus known as HOHO DELHI, modelled on popular concept of transport facilities in Western countries.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The bus, which is equipped with state-of-the-art technologies like digital video screens and GPS systems, also had trained guides who were responsible for giving information about the sites.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] To prepare for the energy-usage spike during the games and to end chronic power cuts in Delhi, the government undertook a large power-production initiative to increase power production to 7000 MW (from the previous 4500 MW).
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] To achieve this the government streamlined the power distribution process, directed additional energy to Delhi, and constructed new power plants.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Indian states trained state police forces to handle tourist-related issues and deploy them prior to the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] A large-scale construction and "beautification" project has resulted in the demolition of hundreds of homes and the displacement of city dwellers—at least 100,000 of New Delhi's 160,000 homeless people have removed from shelters, some of which have been demolished.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Bamboo screens have been erected around city slums to separate visitors from the sights of the slums, a practice which human rights campaigners have deemed dishonest and immoral.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The Delhi High Court implemented a series of "mobile courts" to be dispatched throughout Delhi to relocate migrant beggars from Delhi streets.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The mobile courts would consider each beggar on a case-by-case basis to determine whether the beggar should be sent back to his/her state of residence, or be permitted to remain in government-shelters.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The opening ceremony was held at the Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, the main stadium of the event, in New Delhi, India.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The opening ceremony was directed by Ganapathy Bharat, known commonly as Bharat Bala, an acclaimed Tamil film director, screenwriter and film producer based in Kodambakkam, Chennai.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The ceremony featured over 8,000 performers, and lasted for two-and-a-half hours.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] It is estimated that ₹ 3.50 billion (US$77 million) were spent to produce the ceremony.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The ceremony was divided into six separate segments, each showcasing the rich, ancient and diverse cultures of India, including art, traditions, dances, music and colours.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] It began with a showcase of a variety of drummers from all parts of India, accompanied by seven-year-old tabla player Keshav.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The countdown took place on a screen in the stadium, and was accompanied by fireworks.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The centerpiece of the ceremony was the helium aerostat, which acted as a giant 360° screen for spectators.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The ceremony showcased a fusion of various classical dances from all parts of India, mehendi decorations, sand paintings and yoga.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The title song was performed by A R Rahman.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Singer Hariharan sang the welcome song for the Games, titled "Swagatam", with thousands of school children.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The Prince of Wales (now Charles III; representing Elizabeth II as Head of the Commonwealth) and President of India Pratibha Patil officially declared the Games open.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Prime Minister Manmohan Singh of the host nation, India, attended the opening ceremony as well.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] A total of three heads of state from outside India attended the opening ceremony; two from Commonwealth nations and one from a non-Commonwealth nation.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The three head of states were Mohamed Nasheed, President of the Maldives, Marcus Stephen, President of Nauru and a multiple Commonwealth gold medallist, and Albert II, Prince of Monaco, representing the International Olympic Committee.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] As well, Sir Anand Satyanand, the Governor General of New Zealand, attended the ceremony.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The closing ceremony featuring both Indian and Scottish performers.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The closing ceremony was not as well received as the opening ceremony.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The Commonwealth Games flag was handed over to representatives of Glasgow, Scotland, which hosted the XX Commonwealth Games in 2014.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] At the closing ceremony, the President of the Commonwealth Games Federation declared that Delhi had hosted a "truly exceptional Games".
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] There were 71 participating nations at the 2010 Commonwealth Games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] As Fiji was suspended from the Commonwealth, it was banned from participating in the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Rwanda fielded a team for the games for the first time after becoming a Commonwealth member in 2009.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The numbers of athletes from each country is shown in brackets.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] There were events in 21 disciplines across 17 sports for the 2010 Commonwealth Games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Kabaddi was a demonstration sport at the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Triathlon was excluded from the games as there was no suitable location for the swimming stage.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The organisers have also removed basketball, but included archery, tennis and wrestling.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Cricket, although in strong demand, did not make a comeback as the Board of Control for Cricket in India were not keen on a Twenty20 tournament, and the organisers did not want a one day tournament.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Only the top ten nations by medal rank are shown in this medal table.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Nations are ranked first by count of gold medals, then silver medals, then bronze medals.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The ranking in this table is consistent with International Olympic Committee convention in its published medal tables.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] By default, the table is ordered by the number of gold medals the athletes from a nation have won (in this context, a "nation" is an entity represented by an NOC).
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The number of silver medals is taken into consideration next and then the number of bronze medals.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] If nations are still tied, equal ranking is given and they are listed alphabetically by IOC country code.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] In Boxing two bronze medals were awarded in each weight class.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Additionally there was a tie of three athletes for the third place in the women's pole vault in athletics meant that three bronze medals were awarded.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Therefore, the total number of bronze medals is greater than the total number of gold or silver medals.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The host broadcast activities were provided by SIS Live, the production house, in partnership with Prasar Bharati, the host broadcaster, which includes Doordarshan.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] In New Zealand, the rights were first won by TVNZ.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] In September 2009, it was reported that TVNZ were seeking to offload the rights to SKY TV to avoid a NZ$5 million loss in the event, and the deal was confirmed in January 2010, backed by the country's government.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Although Sky is a pay television broadcaster, they still promised that the coverage would be broadcast free-to-air.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The official motto for the 2010 Commonwealth Games was "Come out and play".
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] It was chosen to represent the invitation of the athletes from the Commonwealth member countries to participate in the games and achieve success as well as the call of the Indian people to support their country's hosting of the games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The logo of the 2010 Commonwealth Games is an image of Chakra, India's national symbol of freedom, unity, power and progress.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The silhouette of the figures spiralling upwards from the Chakra, represents the growth of India into a vibrant nation and the games motto, Come out and play.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The logo consists of six colours which are green, red, yellow, blue, purple and pink.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Green represents life, energy, high spirits, the 2010 games as a green games and determination in overcoming challenges, purple represents reassurance, mystery and excitement, red represents unity, yellow represents destiny, blue represents equality while pink represents luxury and surprise.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The official mascot for the 2010 Commonwealth Games was *Shera*, an anthropomorphised tiger.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] His name comes from "Sher", a Hindi word meaning tiger (Hindi "Bagh" means tiger, however, Sher can be colloquially used for both lion and tiger).
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Shera is described as being the older brother of Jigrr, the mascot of the 2008 Commonwealth Youth Games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The logo and the look for the games were designed by Idiom Design and Consulting.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Indian Railways served as the lead partner of the 2010 Commonwealth Games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Central Bank of India, Air India and NTPC Limited served as the official partners for banking, airline and power respectively.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Hero Honda was the official motorcycle partner as well as the presenting partner of the Queen's Baton Relay.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Tata Motors served as the vehicle transport sponsor by providing vehicles and its maintenance services during the Queen's Baton Relay.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Swiss watchmaker Tissot was the official timekeeper sponsor of the games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The official song of the 2010 Commonwealth Games "Jiyo Utho Badho Jeeto" was composed and performed by the Indian musician A.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The song's title is based on the slogan of the games, "Come out and play".
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The song was written by Mehboob in Hindi with a sprinkling of English words.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The music video, directed by Bharath Bala was released on 23 September and featured a shorter version of the song.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Rahman also gave a live concert for the theme song in Gurgaon, Haryana, which was previewed on various news channels.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The official video of the song has been released on YouTube.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] However this song was not much appreciated by the people as it was being compared with 2010 FIFA World Cup South Africa's official song Waka Waka (This Time for Africa) of Shakira.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The negative pre-event publicity and heavy security presence played a part in low spectator attendance during the initial events.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] However the numbers picked up as the Games progressed.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The day after the conclusion of the Games, the Indian Government announced the formation of a special committee to probe the allegations of corruption and mismanagement against the Organising Committee.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The probe committee will be led by former Comptroller and Auditor General of India VK Shunglu.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] This probe will be in addition to the Central Bureau of Investigation, Enforcement Directorate, and Central Vigilance Commission investigations already underway.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The Prime Minister of India, Dr Manmohan Singh had promised in mid-August, when reports of the bungling first surfaced, that corrupt officials will be given "severe and exemplary" punishment after the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The probe committee is tasked with looking into "all aspects of organising and conducting" the Games, and "to draw lessons from it." It was given three months to submit its report, but the report was never publicly released.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The Indian Sports Ministry directed the Organising Committee of the 2010 Commonwealth Games, to not release any staffer from their positions until the probe committee's work is finished.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] One of the aims of hosting the Commonwealth Games was to build world-class athletics infrastructure within the country, expose audiences to top-level non-cricket competition and encourage the youth to "Come out and play" (the official theme of the games).
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] Building a sporting culture that looks beyond cricket is seen as an important task for a country which won its first ever individual Olympic gold medal in Beijing 2008, despite having the world's second-largest population.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] To build a truly global capacity in sport, you have to take it round the world – out of your own backyard.
[src:aberdeen/2010-commonwealth-games] The country will again stage the Commonwealth Games in 2030, this time held in Ahmedabad, Gujarat.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] A census of the population of the United Kingdom is taken every ten years.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The **2011 census** was held in all countries of the UK on 27 March 2011.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] It was the first UK census which could be completed online via the Internet.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics (ONS) is responsible for the census in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) is responsible for the census in Scotland, and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) is responsible for the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is the executive office of the UK Statistics Authority, a non-ministerial department formed in 2008 and which reports directly to Parliament.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS is the UK Government's single largest statistical producer of independent statistics on the UK's economy and society, used to assist the planning and allocation of resources, policy-making and decision-making.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS designs, manages and runs the census in England and Wales.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In its capacity as the national statistics office for the United Kingdom, ONS also compiles and releases census tables for the United Kingdom when the data from England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland are complete.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In the run-up to the census both the main UK political parties expressed concerns about the increasing cost and the value for money of the census, and it was suggested that the 2011 census might be the last decennial census to be taken.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results from the 2011 census, age and sex, and occupied households estimates for England and Wales and Northern Ireland, were released on 16 July 2012.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results for Scotland, and the first UK-wide results, were published on 17 December 2012.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed and specialised data were published from 2013.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Registrar General John Rickman conducted the first census of Great Britain's population, and was responsible for the ten-yearly reports published between 1801 and 1831.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the first 100 years of census-taking the population of England and Wales grew more than threefold, to around 32 million, and that of Scotland, where a separate census has been carried out since 1861, to about 4.5 million.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 1911 onwards rapid social change, scientific breakthroughs, and major world events affected the structure of the population.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] A fire that destroyed census records in 1931, and the declaration of war in 1939, made the 1951 census hugely significant in recording 30 years of change over one of the most turbulent periods in British history.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 1971 census was run by the newly created Office of Population Censuses and Surveys (OPCS), a body formed by the merger of the General Register Office and Government Social Survey.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 1996 the Office for National Statistics (ONS) was formed by merging the Central Statistical Office (CSO), OPCS and the statistics division of the Department of Employment; the first census it ran was in 2001.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2008 the UK Statistics Authority was established as an independent body.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] A population census is a key instrument for assessing the needs of local communities.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] When related to other data sources such as housing or agricultural censuses, or sample surveys, the data becomes even more useful.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Most countries of the world take censuses: the United Nations recommends that countries take a census at least once every ten years.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Twenty-one out of 40 countries in Europe are engaged in the 2010–2011 census round The design for the 2011 census reflected changes in society since 2001 and asked questions to help paint a detailed demographic picture of England and Wales, as it stood on census day, 27 March 2011.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Data collected by the census is used to provide statistical outputs which central government uses to plan and allocate local authority services funding, and which local authorities themselves use to identify and meet the needs of their local communities.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Other organisations that use census data include healthcare organisations, community groups, researchers and businesses.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questionnaires, including people's personal information, are kept confidential for 100 years before being released to the public, providing an important source of information for historical, demographic and genealogy research.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for England and Wales included around 25 million households.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] People could complete and submit their questionnaire online, or fill it in on paper and post it back in a pre-addressed envelope.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Guidance was provided online and through the census helpline.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Completed questionnaires were electronically tracked and field staff followed up with households that did not return a questionnaire.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In these cases field staff delivered and collected questionnaires and, where needed, provided advice or assistance in completing the questionnaire.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] There was a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] As at 27 March 2011 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Failure to return a completed questionnaire could lead to a fine and criminal record.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK, the UK arm of US-based aerospace, defence, security, and technology company Lockheed Martin was awarded the contract to provide services for the census comprising questionnaire printing, a customer contact centre and data capture and processing.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The contract was valued at £150 million, approximately one third of the total £482 million census budget.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Concerns were raised during contract negotiations that the US PATRIOT Act could be used to force Lockheed Martin to reveal census data to US authorities.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several groups called for a boycott of the census over the involvement of Lockheed Martin, including the Stop the War Coalition, and the Christian thinktank Ekklesia.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The groups were concerned about sharing data with a company involved in surveillance and data processing for the CIA and FBI; and also providing funding to an arms company making nuclear missiles and cluster bombs.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Green Party also objected, and campaigned unsuccessfully to stop Lockheed Martin getting the contract, although no decision was made about whether or not to call for a boycott.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Census Alert campaign group also decided against calling for a boycott.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy said a boycott would be counter-productive, as the census is used to distribute funding to local services.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy reports that a council may lose £22,000 over 10 years for each person who does not complete the census.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The census for England and Wales was trialled in 135,000 households in Lancaster, the London Borough of Newham and Anglesey on 11 October 2009.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] A test was also carried out in Birmingham at the same time.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questions for the 2011 census were the same as those trialled in the 2009 Census Rehearsal.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Order for the 2011 Census (including the proposed question topics, census date and who should complete the questionnaire) was laid before Parliament in October 2009 and was approved by Parliament and became law in December 2009.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Capita Group was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 35,000 temporary ONS workers who worked as field staff for the 2011 census.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The total cost of the 2011 census in England and Wales over the period from 2004/05 to 2015/16 is estimated to be £482 million.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] This is more than twice the £210m spent on the 2001 census.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] This breaks down to a cost of 87 pence per person, per year (over the life of the census – ten years).
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] "The cost equates to about 87p a year per person, demonstrating excellent value for money.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The per capita costs in the UK are less than for many other European countries that carry out similar censuses.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In summary, this census will meet crucial requirements for statistical information that Government and others cannot do without." Minister of State, Cabinet Office (Angela E.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Both the main UK political parties had expressed concerns about the rising costs and value of a ten-yearly census, and on coming into office the UK coalition government had gone as far as suggesting that the 2011 census might be the last of its kind.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In July 2010 the UK government asked ONS to explore other methods of measuring the population.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 the three national statistics bodies, ONS, GROS and NISRA set up a co-ordinated research project known as Beyond 2011.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The project reported its findings in March 2014 and recommended that a UK-wide census in 2021 should take place, and that better use should be made of other demographic data sources.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The general style of the questionnaire was similar to that of the 2001 census.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal questionnaire was released in 2009.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several new identity and status options were included for the first time.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2001 only 38 people were reported to have been prosecuted for refusing to complete a questionnaire.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 those who refused to complete the census questionnaire or included false information could face a fine of up to £1,000.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] A team of compliance staff were recruited to follow up by visiting those householders who refused to complete a questionnaire or where their questionnaire was not returned or completed correctly.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Advertising promoted the notion of how the UK 2011 census would help to shape Britain's future in areas such as healthcare and education.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] TV adverts, for example, depicted Origami, in census colours, forming objects including school computers and buses.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] A short sentence under the census logo informed the viewer that the census was a duty that must be undertaken.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 7 April 2011 advertising focused on reminding people to complete and return by post or submit online.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] A question about the number of bedrooms a household has, as well as the names, gender and birth dates of any overnight guests was criticised as "bedroom snooping" by the Conservative Party in opposition.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Although some 37,000 people recorded their identity as Cornish by manually writing it on the form in the 2001 census, no tick-box was provided in 2011 to select Cornish as a White British national identity, despite campaigns.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] As a consequence, posters were created by the census organisation and Cornwall Council which advised residents of how they could identify themselves as Cornish by writing it in the ethnicity, national identity and main language sections.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, people could record Cornwall as their country of birth.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the consultation on the 2011 census the British Humanist Association raised several concerns about question 20, "What is your religion?".
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA argued it was a leading question, and suggested that it should be phrased as two questions, "Do you have a religion?" and "If so, what is it?".
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] It contended that by placing the religion question near the ethnicity question it would encourage some responders to associate religion with cultural identity.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA also ran adverts during March 2011 encouraging the use of the 'no religion' box in the questionnaire.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland had 59 questions in total.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] 14 were about the household and its accommodation and 45 questions were for each individual member of the household to complete.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The rehearsal was held on Sunday 11 October 2009 in two areas, Derriaghy and Moy & Benburb, covering approximately 5,000 households.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland costing around £21.8 million over the six-year period 2008–2014.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Over the ten-year cycle the cost is expected to be about £25 million.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, a wholly owned subsidiary of information technology company CACI was contracted to gather information.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] CACI "provided interrogators who worked at Abu Ghraib prison at the height of the prisoner abuse scandal".
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 Scotland census asked 13 household questions and up to 35 questions for each individual.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Plans were rehearsed in west Edinburgh and Lewis and Harris.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census was the first to include a question asking about the ability to read, write and understand the Scots language alongside the question for ability in Scottish Gaelic and English languages.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Responsibility for the release of data from the 2011 census is split between the Office for National Statistics (ONS) for England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) for Scotland and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The ONS announced in March the release plan for the results of the 2011 census which stated in July 2012.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA made a similar announcement with identical release plan.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In June 2012 GROS advised on its release plan which commences in December 2012.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The releases will comprise data sets enabling the standard comparison with previous census data reports as well as over a hundred new data sets based on the new questions asked in the 2011 census.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA, ONS and GROS each publish a schedule stating what documents they will release and when.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Those documents are called a "prospectus".
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each prospectus is not fixed, but changes as schedules are changed or documents are late.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The prospectuses are linked to in the table below.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is responsible for publishing United Kingdom wide 2011 census data.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] These are co-ordinated releases coinciding with data published by the three national statistical authorities.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population data including data for males and females for the United Kingdom and revised estimates England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population numbers (rounded), by five-year age bands, sex and densities and household sata at national and local authority level.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates (unrounded) by single year of age and sex for the UK and all local authorities (or equivalent) in the UK, along with UK historic population pyramids (1951–2011).
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 1 – Census Profiles; Population, People and Places, Health and Social Care, Travel and Transport.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] National and Local Authority geographies.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 2 – Census Profiles; Qualifications and Labour Market.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 3 – Multivariate, Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for: Living arrangements; Household composition; and Accommodation type.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] A series of further releases, subsequent to the four main releases of 2011 Census statistics including migration tables, workplace tables, detailed religion and ethnic group tables, and statistics relating to alternative population bases.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Specialist products would include:- Small population groups; microdata; flow data (also known as origin-destination statistics).
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] It is also suggested that data organised around alternative population bases may be produced.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The original plans of the ONS, covering England and Wales, confirmed that there would be four stages of data release starting in July 2012 and running until October 2013.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] This was increased to five stages in October 2013.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] A detailed commentary accompanies each release along with relevant reference materials.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally there will be graphic visualisations providing further clarification and comparison between different data sets and comparison over time using data from earlier censuses.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] There will also be more specialist reports and products.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Certain data bases will also be produced in the Welsh language.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick univariate (single parameter) statistics based on output levels, with release based on geography.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] (e.g. local authority, wards and parish/ community) tabulated by population count and percentages and accessible by post code.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key Statistics for local authorities in England and Wales comprising data which adds detail to the population estimates published in July 2012.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] It includes population information on international migration, age, ethnicity, national identity, health, housing and religion.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Wales, there is data on the Welsh language and population data on unitary authorities.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for Output Areas (OAs) and for wards.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Background information covering families, general health and disability, unpaid care, language, occupation and industry, qualifications and economic activity.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics for postcode sectors, health areas and Welsh Government devolved constituencies, and the key statistics for national parks in England and Wales, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for non-UK short-term residents in England and Wales and quick statistics for England and Wales on national identity, passports held and country of birth, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed cross tabulation of data topics: Migration; ethnicity, identity, language and religion; health; and Welsh tables.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed Characteristics tables for the themes of demography and families at local authority, MSOA and ward level.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] English language proficiency for regions, local authorities, 2011 Census Merged Wards and MSOAs in England and Wales.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first Local Characteristics tables for the topics of ethnicity, identity, language and religion for Output Areas, unitary and local authorities and regions.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics tables for the topics of health and unpaid care for Output Areas.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Follow up to Release 3.2b on 12 July 2013.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristic Tables for the topic of migration for Output Areas.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics on travel to work and car and van availability for Output Areas.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the six main releases phases further supplementary, smaller scale and specialist releases including; Small population groups, Microdata (teaching files, safeguarded files and secure files), Origin-destination data, and Alternate population bases.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Northern Ireland were set out by the NISRA.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release phases are closely synchronised with those of the ONS for England and Wales with some marginal variations to allow for local administrative arrangements.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex for Local Government Districts, etc.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Household number and size by geographic units.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key statistics for NI and Local Government Districts etc.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Quick statistics for all geographies and population and household estimates for lower geographies.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI-wide and all local authority and other geographies (including religion, identity and health).
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI (including ethnicity, country of birth and language).
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Remaining detailed characteristics for NI including labour market and housing.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] All outstanding detailed characteristics for the remaining geographic areas.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate local characteristic tables and detailed themes around: economic activity; country of birth; occupation; and unpaid care.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Scotland were set out by the GROS Release phase dates are partly in sync with those of the other UK constituent country statistical authorities, however the first release was scheduled for six months after the first releases by the other authorities.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Consequently, release of UK-wide data has been scheduled so as to coincide with release plans for Scotland's Census releases.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates, based on resident households, communal establishments and age bands.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Estimates of the usually resident population of Scotland rounded to the nearest thousand, broken down by age and sex.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] An estimate of the total population in each council area, rounded to nearest thousand.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates by five-year age bands and sex for Scotland and each council area.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population and household changes since 2001 census.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population dependency ratios for Scotland and each council area.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] First release of unrounded population estimates and household communal establishment numbers, by single year of age and sex.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] (First published as rounded data in December 2012 and March 2013).
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics; Census Profiles; headcounts and geography products.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Comprising; Estimates by postcode and geography products.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] This release will represent the start of the dissemination of detailed census statistics for small areas.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for marriage and civil partnership, ethnicity, religion, language proficiency, country of birth and national identity, heath (excluding long-term health), age, arrival in UK, population and households, housing and accommodation, car and van ownership.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: Scotland, Council Areas and Health Boards.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Education and Labour Market.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All output areas and Data Zones.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Also the key and quick statistics for the remaining geographies of the topics covered in Release 2a.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Living Arrangements and Travel to Work Methods.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All levels of census geographies.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate statistics, comprising a combination of; age, sex, resident type, ethnic group, economic activity, general health and provision of unpaid care, country of birth, and occupation.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for Qualifications, Employment and Economic Activity, Travel for Work and Study.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables including; Travel to Work, Household, Qualifications and Long-term Health, Social Status and Economic Activity.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The United Kingdom Statistics Authority is responsible for coordinating the release of census data by the devolved statistics authorities.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] It publishes UK-wide census data results via the Office for National Statistics (ONS) site.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The UK Data Service provides a central point of reference for all country-specific census data releases via its Learning Hub site.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Primary responsibility for country-specific 2011 census data rests with the statistical authorities for each of the UK's constituent countries.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each authority has at least one dedicated central source from which data can be downloaded or ordered.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] For England and Wales the ONS provides the access to primary data via its 2011 census siteArchived 29 January 2016 at the UK Government Web Archive.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, data organised by local authority or post code is available on the Neighbourhood Statistics Archived 20 October 2010 at the Wayback Machine site, and nomis, a source of detailed census results which can be assembled into bespoke data sets.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Scotland the General Registrar Office for Scotland (GROS) part of National Records of Scotland (NRS) to maintain access via its Scotlands Census site, and for Northern Ireland the Statistics and Research Authority (NISRA) uses the Northern Ireland Neighbourhood Information Service (NINIS).
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The format of all the pre-defined statistical tables is standardised as far as practical across the publishing authorities.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] Since the 2001 UK census the naming conventions for the tables have been revised following research into the approaches adopted by other census publishing bodies around the world.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] The statistical authorities are also making available bulk data in Comma-separated values (CSV) file format which can be downloaded from online data warehouse facilities.
[src:aberdeen/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the standard releases and online bulk access the statistical authorities provide a commissioned data service whereby other data configurations can be purchased, under license, by customers and will subsequently be made freely available to other users.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The **2012 Summer Paralympics**, branded as the **London 2012 Paralympic Games**, were an international multi-sport parasports event held from 29 August to 9 September 2012 in London, England, United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] They were the 14th Summer Paralympic Games as organised by the International Paralympic Committee (IPC).
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] These Games were the first Summer Paralympics to be hosted by London and the first to be hosted solely by Great Britain.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The English village of Stoke Mandeville had previously co-hosted the 1984 Games with Long Island, New York, after the original host—the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign—withdrew due to financial difficulties.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] In 1948, the village hosted the Stoke Mandeville Games—the first organised sporting event for athletes with disabilities, and a precursor to the modern Paralympic Games—to coincide with the opening of the 1948 Olympics in London.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] For the third Summer Paralympics in a row, China won the most medals overall, with a total of 231 (95 of them being gold), followed by Russia and Great Britain.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] As part of a formal agreement between the International Paralympic Committee and the International Olympic Committee established in 2001, the winner of the bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics was also to host the 2012 Summer Paralympics.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] At the 117th IOC Session in Singapore, the rights to host the 2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympics were awarded to London.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] As with the Olympics, the 2012 Summer Paralympics were overseen by the London Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games (LOCOG) and the Olympic Delivery Authority (ODA).
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] LOCOG was responsible for overseeing the staging of the games, while the ODA dealt with infrastructure and venues.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The Government Olympic Executive (GOE) within the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) was the lead Government body for co-ordinating the London 2012 Olympics and Paralympics.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The GOE reported through the DCMS Permanent Secretary to the Minister for Sports and the Olympics Hugh Robertson.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] It focused on oversight of the Games, cross-programme management and the London 2012 Olympic Legacy.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] England's role in the history of the Paralympics was emphasised as part of the Games: an event known as the Stoke Mandeville Games were hosted by the village of Stoke Mandeville—site of the National Spinal Injuries Centre—to coincide with the opening of the 1948 Summer Olympics in London.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Contested between British veterans of the Second World War, it was the first organised sporting event for athletes with disabilities, and served as a precursor to the modern Paralympic Games.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Facilities of the 2012 Summer Paralympics in the Greater London area.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The 2012 Summer Paralympics used many of the same venues as the 2012 Summer Olympics, along with two exclusive venues (Eton Manor for wheelchair tennis and Brands Hatch circuit for road cycling.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] All the London's purpose-built Olympic venues and facilities, including the Olympic Village, were designed with accessibility in mind so that they could accommodate the Paralympics.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Some older venues also contained additional accessible seating areas during the Paralympics.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Transport for London (TfL) operated the Paralympic Route Network (a downsized version of the Olympic Route Network operated during the Summer Olympics) to facilitate road traffic between venues and facilities.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The network provided 8.7 miles (14.0 kilometres) of lanes specifically reserved for Paralympic athletes and officials.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] TfL continued to operate its *Get Ahead of the Games* website during the Paralympics, which provided updates and advice for commuters during the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Prior to the Games, concerns were raised by TfL commissioner Peter Hendy that London's transportation system might not be able to handle the Paralympics adequately.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] He feared that the end of the school summer holiday (which fell during the Games) would result in increased traffic, and that commuters might not heed traffic warnings or change their travel behaviour as they had during the Olympics.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Sevenoaks railway station was designated as the preferred station for spectators travelling to watch the cycling at Brands Hatch.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Organisers chose Sevenoaks over the closer Swanley railway station because of its "existing step-free access and excellent transport links", and because Swanley did not yet have a wheelchair lift.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Whilst organisers did not believe that Swanley would be able to have wheelchair lifts installed by the start of the Paralympics, the station finished their installation by early August 2012.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The formal handover occurred during the closing ceremony of the 2008 Summer Paralympics in Beijing, when Mayor of London Boris Johnson received the Paralympic Flag from Mayor of Beijing Guo Jinlong.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] This was followed by a cultural presentation by Britain, which was a which was a sequel to the presentation during the Antwerp Ceremony during the Olympics closing ceremonies.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] It featured urban dance group ZooNation, the Royal Ballet, and Candoco, a physically integrated dance group, all dressed as London commuters and waiting for a bus by a zebra crossing.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] A double-decker bus drove around the stadium, guided by Ade Adepitan, to music composed by Philip Sheppard.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The top of the bus was open and folded down to show a privet hedge featuring London landmarks such as Tower Bridge, The Gherkin and the London Eye.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Cherisse Osei, drummer for Mika, and Sam Hegedus then performed, before the top of the bus folded up into its original form, sporting multi-coloured Paralympic livery.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Both the Paralympic and Olympic flags were formally raised outside of London's City Hall on 26 September 2008.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] British Paralympians Helene Raynsford and Chris Holmes raised the Paralympic flag.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] On 8 September 2011, Trafalgar Square staged *International Paralympic Day* to coincide with a visit to London by representatives of the IPC.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Hosted by Rick Edwards, Ade Adepitan and Iwan Thomas, the event featured showcases and demonstrations of the 20 sports that would feature during the Games, with some sessions also made inclusive to people with hearing disabilities.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] It also included appearances by Paralympic athletes Oscar Pistorius, Ellie Simmonds and Sascha Kindred, and the unveiling of a bronze statue of Pistorius by Ben Dearnley.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Prime Minister David Cameron and Mayor of London Boris Johnson also appeared.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Two days later on 10 September, supermarket chain Sainsbury's and Channel 4 presented *Sainsbury's Super Saturday*, a family event at Clapham Common.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The event featured showcases of Paralympic sports, and a concert featuring pop music acts including Nicola Roberts, Olly Murs, The Wanted, Will Young, Pixie Lott, Dappy, Sugababes, The Saturdays, Chipmunk and Taio Cruz.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Channel 4—the new broadcaster of the Paralympics in Great Britain—developed a multi-platform advertising campaign to promote its coverage.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The broadcaster sought to change the public perception of the Paralympics, encouraging viewers to see them as an "event in its own right", rather than as an afterthought to the Olympics.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The campaign included television adverts, online content, and billboard advertising, some of which carrying the slogan "Thanks for the warm-up".
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] As part of the campaign, Channel 4 produced a two-minute-long trailer for its coverage entitled *Meet the Superhumans*, which was directed by Tom Tagholm with input from Deborah Poulton, 2012 Paralympic Project Leader and Alison Walsh, Editorial Manager of Disability, both at Channel 4.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The trailer, set to Public Enemy's song "Harder Than You Think", focused on the competitive and "superhuman" aspects of Paralympic sport, while acknowledging the personal events and struggles that reflected every athlete's participation in the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] *Meet the Superhumans* premiered on 17 July 2012, airing simultaneously on 78 different commercial television channels in the UK (which included rival commercial channels ITV and Sky1).
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] In August 2009, Royal Mail unveiled a series of 30 stamps (reflecting the 30th Olympiad) in honour of the 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games, released in batches of ten between 2009 and July 2011.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Each stamp featured an Olympic or Paralympic sport and the London 2012 logo.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Royal Mail initially defended its decision, arguing that it would have been "logistically and practically impossible" to issue individual stamps for each gold medallist, since it expected the British team to meet or exceed its performance at Beijing of 42 gold medals.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] As a result of the criticism, Royal Mail announced on 15 August 2012 that it would release individual stamps for each British gold medallist during the Paralympics.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The Paralympic torch relay began on 22 August, when groups of integrated scouts kindled four Paralympic flames on the highest peaks of each Home Nation: Scafell Pike in England, Ben Nevis in Scotland, Slieve Donard in Northern Ireland, and Snowdon in Wales.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] On 24 August the four flames were used to light ceremonial cauldrons in London, Edinburgh, Belfast and Cardiff during special "Flame Festival" events; smaller "Flame Celebration" events were also held in various communities over the bank holiday weekend.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] On 28 August the four flames were united during a ceremony at Stoke Mandeville Stadium.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The flame then travelled a 92-mile (148-kilometre) route to Olympic Stadium in a 24-hour relay, with 580 torchbearers working in teams of five.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] After a two-hour weather delay, a backup flame was taken straight to the stadium as a contingency, and the relay route was modified.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] However, as the opening ceremony's parade of nations took longer than expected, the flame was able to reach the external area of Olympic Stadium in time.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] 2.7 million tickets were offered in total, including event-specific tickets and those granting access solely to the Olympic Park, along with multi-event passes offered for ExCeL London and Olympic Park that were intended to allow spectators to discover a variety of Paralympic events.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Unlike previous Paralympics, tickets were in extremely high demand, and the ticket allocation was increased from the originally planned 2.5 million.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Whilst the period during the Olympics has historically been the busiest for Paralympic sales, 1.4 million tickets were already sold before the start of the Summer Olympics, already surpassing the total number sold in Sydney.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The high demand resulted in the Ticketmaster-operated website crashing under the load.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] On 8 August, LOCOG announced that 2.1 million tickets had been sold (600,000 in the previous month alone), breaking the record of 1.8 million set in Beijing (1.6 million tickets were also distributed by the Chinese government).
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] IPC president Philip Craven congratulated London for this achievement, crediting it to "the insatiable appetite the public has for top class elite sport", and noted it would be fitting for a Paralympics held in its spiritual birthplace to have filled venues.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] By the opening ceremony, 2.4 million had been sold, with the remaining 100,000 sold during the Games; 10,000 were offered each day.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The last 800 tickets to the Opening Ceremony were distributed to police and the military, while Mayor Boris Johnson arranged for the distribution of 1,100 to members of London's youth athletics clubs.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Due to popular demand, a further 100,000 contingency tickets were released on 6 September (which included multi-event passes, and event tickets given up by sponsors and partners), along with 100,000 giving access solely to the Olympic Park.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The emblems for the 2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympics were unveiled on 4 June 2007; designed by Wolff Olins, it is a stylized representation of the number "2012".
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The official mascot of the 2012 Summer Paralympic Games, Mandeville, was unveiled alongside its Olympic counterpart Wenlock on 19 May 2010.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] As characters, they are portrayed as drops of steel from a steelworks in Bolton, and feature singular camera eyes —representing "focus"— with the cameras capturing aspects of the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Mandeville is named in honour of Stoke Mandeville due to its significance in the origins of the Paralympics.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Mandeville also wears a helmet emblazoned in the red, green, and blue colours of the Paralympic emblem.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The opening ceremony was held on 29 August at the Olympic Stadium.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] It was inspired by William Shakespeare's play *The Tempest* and themed around the concept of "Enlightenment", with actors Ian McKellen and Nicola Miles-Wildin playing the roles of Prospero and Miranda.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] It featured appearances by theoretical physicist Stephen Hawking, and performances by British electronic music group Orbital, and the Graeae Theatre Company, who performed Ian Dury's 1981 protest song "Spasticus Autisticus".
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The final bearers of the Paralympic flame represented several generations of Paralympic athletes.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] "Future" Paralympic athlete Joe Townsend, a Royal Marine who lost both of his legs after stepping on a land mine on duty in Afghanistan, delivered the flame to Olympic Stadium via a zipline from the ArcelorMittal *Orbit* tower.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] He passed the flame to long-time British Five-a-side football captain David Clarke, who then passed it to the lighter of the Paralympic cauldron, Margaret Maughan, who was the winner of Britain's first gold medal at the first official Paralympics, in Rome.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The closing ceremony was held on 9 September at the Olympic Stadium.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Entitled "The Festival of the Flame", the ceremony was themed around the gathering of people in celebration, and was directed by Kim Gavin, who also directed the closing ceremony of the Summer Olympics just a few weeks prior.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The artistic programme of the ceremony was set to live performances by the British rock band Coldplay.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Ellie Simmonds and Jonnie Peacock shared the honour of extinguishing the Paralympic cauldron, sharing its last flame on torches to others throughout the stadium to represent its eternal spirit.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] London 2012 had the largest number of athletes and participating nations of any Paralympic Games before.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] A total of 4,243 athletes from 164 countries competed in the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] This represented an increase of 291 athletes and 18 countries from the 2008 Games, which had 3,952 athletes from 146 countries.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Fourteen countries made their Paralympic debut: Antigua and Barbuda, Brunei, Cameroon, Comoros, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Djibouti, the Gambia, Guinea-Bissau, Liberia, Mozambique, North Korea, San Marino, the Solomon Islands and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Trinidad and Tobago returned to the Games for the first time since 1988.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Andorra made its debut in the Summer Paralympics, having already made three appearances at the Winter Paralympics.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Malawi, which would have been making its debut at the Games, and Botswana, were both due to send delegations but withdrew hours before the opening ceremony citing a lack of government funds.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The programme of the 2012 Summer Paralympics featured events in 20 sports.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The number of events in each sport is noted in parentheses.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Events for athletes with intellectual disabilities (ID class) returned to the Paralympics in athletics, swimming, and table tennis for the first time since 2000.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] ID events had been suspended following the 2000 Summer Paralympics, after the Spanish basketball team was stripped of their gold medals when it was found that only 2 of their 12 team members actually had an intellectual disability.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The IPC introduced a new procedure involving "sports intelligence" testing to better determine eligibility for the ID class.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Also beginning in 2012, sighted guides became eligible to receive medals in certain events; sighted goalkeepers in 5-a-side football, along with guides and pilots in athletics and cycling and boccia assistants were now able to receive medals for their contributions.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Previously in the case of tandem cycling, where a visually-impaired rider takes the rear of the bike with a sighted pilot in front, only the visually-impaired rider actually received a medal.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The official schedule was published on 25 August 2011.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] This table is based on the medal count of the International Paralympic Committee (IPC).
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The ranking is sorted primarily by the number of gold medals earned by a National Paralympic Committee (NPC).
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] If countries are still tied, equal ranking is given and they are listed alphabetically by IPC Country Code.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Broadcast rights to the 2012 Summer Paralympics were sold to local broadcasters by LOCOG, with production of the world feeds sub-contracted to Olympic Broadcasting Services (OBS).
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The Games saw a significant growth in media coverage for the Paralympics; LOCOG reached deals with over 36 broadcasters to televise the Games in over 100 countries.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The games were to be broadcast on television in the United Kingdom by Channel 4, replacing the BBC in a £9 million deal; the BBC still held radio rights, with coverage on BBC Radio 5 Live and 5 Live Sports Extra.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The IPC webcast approximately 780 hours of its coverage through its YouTube channel, with four streams of coverage in English and one in Spanish.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The broadcaster invested around £600,000 towards training new on-air personalities with expertise in parasports, with many of them also having disabilities themselves.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] They would be joined by *Channel 4 News* anchor Jon Snow, and BBC Sport personality Clare Balding.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Channel 4 also broadcast supplemental programming to lead towards the Games, such as Paralympic-focused documentaries, other IPC championships, and the weekly magazine programme *That Paralympic Show*.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] During the Games, comedian Adam Hills (who himself was born without a right leg, and hosted the Australian Broadcasting Corporation's coverage of the Beijing Paralympics) would host *The Last Leg*, a comedic aftershow that followed the conclusion of each night's coverage.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Channel 4's coverage of the Games drew relatively high viewership; its coverage of the opening ceremony was seen by an average of 7.6 million viewers, a 40% share, and peaked at 11.2 million viewers—making it one of Channel 4's most-watched programmes in network history.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Prime time coverage saw an average of 3.3 million viewers nightly, while viewership peaked at 4.5 million viewers during the men's T44 200m final where Alan Oliveira beat Oscar Pistorius for the gold medal.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Its coverage of the closing ceremony peaked at 7.7 million viewers.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Similarly extensive coverage was televised by RTVE in Spain, with approximately 150 hours of live coverage on Teledeporte and TVE HD.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The Australian Broadcasting Corporation aired over 100 hours of coverage across its networks during the Paralympics, with coverage on both ABC1 and ABC2.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Coverage of the Games set viewership records for ABC, peaking at 1.6 million viewers on average (in comparison to 1.3 million in Beijing), while ABC2 peaked at a 4.7% viewership share, beating competing digital networks.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] ABC's coverage was also nominated for a Logie Award for "Most Popular Sports Program".
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] In the United States, NBC Sports provided five-and-a-half hours of coverage in total, and no live coverage.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] NBCSN aired one-hour highlight shows, and NBC broadcast a special recapping the Games on 16 September.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The United States Olympic & Paralympic Committee provided extensive coverage through its own digital outlets.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] Critics and American athletes expressed disappointment at NBC for its decision not to broadcast any live coverage of the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] In Canada, rights were held by Canada's Olympic Broadcast Media Consortium; TSN (English) and RDS (French) produced daily hour-long highlight programs (some of which were aired by CTV Television), while tape-delayed airings of the opening ceremony were carried by Sportsnet One, TSN2, RDS, and RDS2.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The coverage was simulcast with open audio descriptions by AMI-tv, a network which broadcasts programming with accommodations for those who are visually or hearing impaired.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] AMI-tv also broadcast supplemental programming, such as a daily news program from London and a documentary series focusing on Canadian athletes at the Paralympics.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The Telegraph Media Group won the Best Written (print and online) award and Channel 4 won the best broadcast award.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p01] The best radio award went to BBC World Service and Larry Wong working for Edmonton Journal won the best photo prize for his image of Benoit Huot.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] The role of IT company Atos as a technology provider and official sponsor of the Paralympic Games was criticised by disability-rights groups, due to its contract with Britain's Department for Work and Pensions to carry out capability assessments that determine eligibility for disability benefits.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] They argued that Atos's programme had lacked integrity and was intended to help cut government spending, since the assessments have resulted in many workers with disabilities being incorrectly judged as "fit for work" and denied benefits.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] Therefore, the groups considered it hypocritical for Atos to sponsor the Games, whilst simultaneously operating a programme that has negatively affected the lives of residents with disabilities.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] Speaking at the protests, comedian Jeremy Hardy said that the programme's intent to "victimise people with disabilities" was "blatant and shameless".
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] During the opening ceremony some British athletes reportedly obscured the Atos logo on their accreditation passes in protest of their involvement.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] However, an official from the British Paralympic Association denied that this had been the case.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] LOCOG defended Atos's involvement, stating that the company was "a critical and valued member of [the companies] delivering these Games", due to the technologies it has provided, which included information systems for managing volunteers and distributing event results.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] Controversy arose about seating rules for wheelchair users, after two mothers with disabilities accused LOCOG of having discriminatory policies.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] A petition for improved access for families with disabilities, started by one of the mothers on Change.org, quickly collected over 30,000 signatures.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] LOCOG denied having discriminatory policies, stating that parents with disabilities could steward their children in wheelchair seating areas at events with unreserved seats, but may not all be able to sit together at events with reserved seating.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] LOCOG faced further criticism for how it handled the sale of tickets for the wheelchair areas within venues.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] In May 2012 the online sale of tickets for wheelchair areas was replaced by a dedicated telephone hotline.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] Organisers were criticised for their use of an 0844 revenue share number for this hotline, and for neglecting to mention on its ticketing website that calls would be charged by the minute.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] Former sports minister Gerry Sutcliffe viewed this as discrimination against wheelchair users, and called upon LOCOG to compensate those who had used the hotline.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] LOCOG denied that it was receiving additional profits from the phone line, and claimed that a dedicated line was being used to allow customers to receive a service tailored to their individual accessibility needs.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] A minor incident occurred involving blind Member of Parliament David Blunkett, who was attending the opening ceremony alongside a Channel 4 director.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] Blunkett was denied access to his seat at Olympic Stadium because there was no room for his guide dog, and had to watch the ceremony from seats in the stadium's gantry instead.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] However, Blunkett noted that this was an isolated incident and chose not to make an issue of it, simply advising organisers to "seek to find a solution rather than impose a preconceived notion of what is or is not possible".
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] British official broadcaster Channel 4 received some criticism for its coverage of the Paralympics.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] Complaints noted that Channel 4 had shown five ad breaks within the first hour of the ceremony, and that ironically, it had recently broadcast a six-hour long late-night dance music special with no adverts at all.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] Channel 4 defended the criticism by stating that it had broadcast "significantly fewer" commercials than normal for prime time programming during the ceremony, and that the ad breaks were needed in order to help the channel invest in broadcasting programming such as the Paralympics.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] Channel 4 noted that time was needed during the first few days to explain Paralympic events and the classification system to viewers, and that it was operating three additional channels' worth of live coverage throughout the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] The broadcaster also stated that it had to make editorial decisions on which events to air during periods where a large number of events were in progress.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] The amount of live coverage was also affected by Olympic Broadcasting Services, who did not send cameras or provide official television coverage for sports such as cycling, the marathon, and shooting.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] Channel 4's news department did send its own cameramen to film the affected events for highlights, but was unable to broadcast them live.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] In the United States, NBC Sports held the broadcast rights to both the Olympics and Paralympics in 2012.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] NBC had been frequently criticised in past years by American athletes and IPC officials for its minimal coverage of past Paralympics, and it was speculated by critics that NBC's history of inadequate coverage may have impacted New York City's bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympics.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] In 2008, it did not air any coverage while the Games were in progress (neither live or delayed), choosing to air a recap documentary on NBC in November 2008, followed by a week of highlights on Universal Sports.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] While relatively larger than its Beijing coverage, NBC produced only five-and-a-half hours of specials featuring tape delayed highlights of the Games; most of them aired on pay-TV channel NBCSN, while the last aired on NBC a week following the conclusion of the Games.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] No coverage of the opening and closing ceremonies, nor any live coverage, was provided.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] By contrast, some broadcasters (such as the host broadcasters, and broadcasters in Australia and Spain) planned to air at least 100 hours or more of coverage from London, and NBC itself had provided extensive coverage of the London Olympics, which was heavily viewed.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] NBC's lack of coverage drew the ire of American disability rights groups and IPC president Philip Craven, who expressed his disappointment for American athletes and viewers who were unable to fully experience the games on television.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] Craven remarked that "some people think that North America always [leads] on everything, and on this they don't.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] During the women's class F35/36 discus competition, an error in scoring caused the wrong medals to be presented.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] In this combined class event, final standings were determined based on a points calculation.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] The calculation converted distances thrown into points, to account for the different functional impairments of the participating athletes.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] Due to an error in the scoring system, the gold medal in the event was originally awarded to Ukrainian athlete Mariia Pomazan.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] When the mistake was discovered, the recalculated points showed that Chinese athlete Wu Qing had finished first, with Pomazan in second place.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] A second medal ceremony was held, which Pomazan did not attend in protest.
[src:aberdeen/2012-paralympic-games-p02] She was eventually required to return her gold medal.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, the Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:aberdeen/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
